Problem Definition & Goals
    The Business Problem: Unplanned machine downtime causes significant financial loss. Predicting failure allows for Predictive Maintenance.
    The Technical Task: Binary classification to predict if a machine will fail ($Target = 1$) or not ($Target = 0$).
    Evaluation Metric: Use ROC-AUC (Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve). Unlike simple accuracy, ROC-AUC handles the extreme class imbalance in this dataset.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
    In this dataset, failure occurs in less than 2% of cases. You must visualize the "signals" of failure.
        Target Distribution: Visualize the class imbalance using a count plot.
        Feature Correlations: Create a heatmap to see how Torque, Rotational speed [rpm], and Tool wear [min] interact.
        Sensor Analysis: Use box plots to compare Air temperature [K] vs. Process temperature [K]. Often, the temperature difference is a stronger predictor than the absolute values.


Feature Engineering (The "Secret Sauce")
    This is where you win or lose on the leaderboard. Create features that represent physical stress:
        Power: $Power = Torque \times \text{Rotational speed}$ (Standard physics formula).
        Temperature Difference: Process Temperature - Air Temperature.Wear Rate: Tool wear / Torque (How fast is the tool wearing under specific load?).
        Total Failure Count: Sum up the binary indicators like TWF, HDF, PWF, OSF, and RNF to see if multiple issues are brewing simultaneously.

Data Preprocessing
    Encoding: Use Label Encoding or One-Hot Encoding for the Type feature (L, M, H).
    Dropping IDs: Remove the id and Product ID columns so the model doesn't overfit on unique identifiers.
    Scaling: If using Logistic Regression or SVM, apply StandardScaler. For Tree-based models (XGBoost/LGBM), scaling is not strictly necessary.

 Modeling Strategy
    For this Kaggle challenge, Gradient Boosting is king.
        Candidate Models: 
            1.  XGBoost: Excellent at handling tabular data.
            2.  LightGBM: Faster and often more accurate for large datasets.
            3.  CatBoost: Great for handling categorical features automatically
            
        Imbalance Handling: Use the scale_pos_weight parameter in XGBoost or is_unbalance=True in LightGBM to penalize the model more for missing a failure.

        Validation: Use Stratified 5-Fold Cross-Validation to ensure each fold has an equal percentage of "failure" cases.

 Model Interpretation (SHAP)
 Explain why the machine failed. Use a SHAP Summary Plot to show which features contributed most to the prediction. For example: "The model predicted failure because the Torque exceeded 60Nm while the Tool Wear was above 200 min."
 